Day 2: Text Formatting & Links

Today you'll learn how to format text and create hyperlinks.

1. Bold Text
<b> Tag

Makes text bold visually.

<b>Java Developer</b>

Output:
Java Developer

2. Strong Text
<strong> Tag

Makes text important and usually bold.

<strong>Important Notice</strong>

Output:
Important Notice

Interview Question

Difference between <b> and <strong>?

<b> → Only bold appearance.
<strong> → Indicates important content (semantic meaning).

Prefer <strong> in modern HTML.

3. Italic Text
<i> Tag
<i>Learning HTML</i>

Output:
Learning HTML

4. Emphasized Text
<em> Tag
<em>Read Carefully</em>

Output:
Read Carefully

Difference
<i> → Visual italic.
<em> → Adds emphasis/importance.
5. Highlight Text
<mark>HTML is easy</mark>

Output:
<mark>HTML is easy</mark>

6. Small Text
<small>Terms and Conditions Apply</small>

Output:
<small>Terms and Conditions Apply</small>

7. Superscript
x<sup>2</sup>

Output:

x²

8. Subscript
H<sub>2</sub>O

Output:

H₂O

9. Links (Very Important)
Basic Link
<a href="https://www.google.com">
    Google
</a>

Clicking it opens Google.

Open Link in New Tab
<a href="https://www.google.com" target="_blank">
    Open Google
</a>
Important Attribute
Attribute	Purpose
href	URL
target="_blank"	Open in new tab
10. Absolute vs Relative URL
Absolute URL

Full web address:

<a href="https://www.google.com">
    Google
</a>
Relative URL

Points to another file in your project:

<a href="about.html">
    About Page
</a>
